-- Bradesco, Enersis, Famsa, Marfrig, Poderosa: Latin America Equity Preview
-- James Attwood
-- 2010-04-26T08:05:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-26/bradesco-enersis-famsa-marfrig-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Latin American trading. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous
close.  
 The MSCI Latin America Index rose 0.4 percent to 4,193.63.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  
 Brazil  
 Banco Bradesco SA (BBDC4 BS): Brazil’s second-largest
lender by market value said it plans to buy a 2.1 percent stake
in Cielo SA and a 10.7 percent stake in Companhia Brasileira de
Solucoes e Servicos - CBSS. Bradesco slid 0.7 percent to 31.68
reais.  
 Marfrig Alimentos SA (MRFG3 BS): The world’s fourth-biggest
beef producer said MMS Participacoes SA, its controlling
shareholder, bought 9.4 million common shares to increase its
holding to 43 percent of the company’s capital. Marfrig
Alimentos dropped 0.8 percent to 18.65 reais.  
 Chile  
 Enersis SA (ENERSIS CC): The Latin American unit of Spanish
power producer Endesa SA was reiterated “buy” at Celfin
Capital after first-quarter profit exceeded its analysts’
estimate. Enersis rose 0.3 percent to 211.35 pesos.  
 Mexico  
 Grupo Famsa SAB (GFAMSAA MM): The retailer’s banking unit,
Banco Ahorro Famsa, may triple its outstanding loans in five
years as it seeks to increase credit to small businesses, said
the bank’s chief executive officer. The bank, based in Monterrey,
may increase loans to about 30 billion pesos ($2.46 billion)
from 10.3 billion pesos now, Adrian Lozano said in an interview.
Grupo Famsa fell 1.7 percent to 25.32 pesos.  
 Peru  
 Cia. Minera Poderosa SA (PODERC1 PE): The Lima-based
company’s gold miners began a strike in Peru for wage increases.
Worker protests at the mine, in which Votorantim Participacoes
SA’s Cia. Minera Atacocha unit holds a 50 percent stake, clashed
with police, leaving 15 people injured, Poderosa said. The
shares last traded on April 22 at 4 soles.  
